{"cursor":"6556","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Alcohol proof' is a measure of how much alcohol (ethanol) is contained in an\nalcoholic beverage. The term was originally used in the United Kingdom and was\ndefined as 7/4 times the alcohol by volume (ABV). The UK now uses the ABV\nstandard instead of alcohol proof. In the United States, alcoholic proof is\ndefined as twice the percentage of ABV. The measurement of alcohol content and\nthe statement of this content on the bottle labels of distilled beverages (also\ncalled liquors or spirits) is regulated by law in the United States. The purpose\nof the regulation is to provide pertinent information to the consumer.\n","linknr":156,"url":"Degree_proof","recorded":1362565399,"links":24,"instances":["alcoholic_beverage"],"pdf":["http://www.oiml.org/publications/R/R022-e75.pdf","http://www.oiml.org/publications/R/R022-e75.pdf"],"categories":["Alcohol measurement"],"headings":["History","Governmental regulation","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["gravity","alcoholic_beverage"],["gravity","alcoholic_beverage"]],"members":["gravity"],"related":["Alcohol","Ethanol","Alcoholic_beverage","United_Kingdom","Alcohol_by_volume","United_States","Bottle","Distilled_beverage","Distilled_beverage","Gravity_(alcoholic_beverage)","Rum","Gunpowder","Distilled_beverage","Alcohol_by_volume","Standard_drink","Australia","Metabolise","European_Union","International_Organization_of_Legal_Metrology","Volume","Mass","European_Union","European_Union","United_Kingdom","International_Organisation_of_Legal_Metrology","Distilled_beverage","United_Kingdom","European_Union","Code_of_Fede